uences (including from Europe)—the author shows how the emergence of the American adversarial legal culture was a product not only of developments internal to law, but also of wider socioeconomic, political, and cultural debates over whether and how to undertake market regulation and pursue racial equality. As a result, adversarialism came to play a key role in defining American legal institutions and practices, as well as national identity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aAdversary system (Law)zUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aConduct of court proceedingszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aCulture and lawzUnited States. 0aProcedure (Law)zUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aSociological jurisprudencezUnited States. 7aLAW / Legal History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2017z9783110540550oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017z978311062526408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Law 2017z9783110547771oZDB-23-DGC08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831106389810 cprintz978030019807240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300224849423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300224849/original  a978-3-11-062526-4  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017b2017  a978-3-11-063898-1  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGCb2017  aZDB-23-DGGb2017